spec: as3211
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(asyncio)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 661 (as3211): __and__, __or__, __xor__ dict-presence for asyncio types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: asyncio.Task, asyncio.Future, asyncio.Event, asyncio.Lock, asyncio.Semaphore, asyncio.BoundedSemaphore, asyncio.Condition, asyncio.Queue, asyncio.PriorityQueue, asyncio.LifoQueue."
    - "Key finding (__and__): all 10 asyncio classes return false for __and__. The bitwise AND operator (&) is characteristic of integer types and set-like collections; none of the asyncio types are either. asyncio.Event, asyncio.Lock, and asyncio.Condition are synchronization primitives that represent boolean-valued state, but they express that state through await-able methods (wait(), acquire(), notify()) rather than through & expressions. asyncio.Semaphore and asyncio.BoundedSemaphore manage a permit counter, yet define no bitwise operators. asyncio.Task/Future are pending coroutine results with a state machine (PENDING/RUNNING/CANCELLED/FINISHED); & is undefined for tasks. asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue are data structures with a size and contents but no set-algebra semantics."
    - "Key finding (__or__): all 10 asyncio classes return false for __or__. The | operator on classes has acquired new meaning in Python 3.10+ (union types for type hints), but this affects the metaclass machinery — it does not cause class instances to define __or__ in their __dict__. asyncio types are coroutine concurrency primitives, not set-like or integer types. asyncio.Event does not define | for combining events. asyncio.Lock does not define | for lock composition. asyncio.Queue does not define | for queue merging. No asyncio type implements __or__ in its own __dict__."
    - "Key finding (__xor__): all 10 asyncio classes return false for __xor__. Bitwise XOR (^) is defined for integers and sets. asyncio types are neither — they are concurrency primitives built on coroutines, locks, and condition variables. asyncio.Event represents a boolean flag; ^ is not defined for event composition. asyncio.Semaphore tracks an integer counter, but that counter is fully encapsulated behind acquire()/release() — no bitwise arithmetic is exposed. asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue store items in ordered collections; ^ is not defined for queue symmetric-difference operations."
    - "Continues the all-false pattern from wave 660 (__pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__). asyncio is a pure coroutine concurrency library: its types interact exclusively through await, async with, async for, and explicit method calls — never through Python's arithmetic or bitwise data model."
    - "Cross-wave summary for asyncio subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (as3076): __get__ — Task/Future/Queue/Handle true; others false."
    - "  Wave 653 (as3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ — selected true."
    - "  Wave 654 (as3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ — TimerHandle true; others false."
    - "  Wave 655 (as3121): __ge__ — TimerHandle true; __repr__ — 12 classes true."
    - "  Wave 656 (as3136): __call__/__len__/__getitem__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 657 (as3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 658 (as3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 659 (as3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 14."
    - "  Wave 660 (as3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 10."
    - "  Wave 661 (as3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 10."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __and__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__and__')
#
# All 10 asyncio classes return false for __and__.
# asyncio types are coroutine-based concurrency primitives, not integer or
#   set-like types. None define bitwise AND in their own __dict__.
# asyncio.Event/Lock/Condition: boolean-state synchronization objects;
#   & is not defined for composing or combining these primitives.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore: permit-counter objects; the internal
#   counter is managed solely through acquire()/release() coroutines — no
#   bitwise operators are exposed on the counter or the semaphore itself.
# asyncio.Task/Future: pending coroutine result handles; & is undefined.
# asyncio.Queue/PriorityQueue/LifoQueue: ordered item stores with no
#   set-algebra semantics — get()/put() are the entire interface.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

