    - ["as3211030", operator.contains, [asyncio.LifoQueue.__dict__,        "__xor__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __and__, __or__, __xor__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __and__: false for all 10 — bitwise AND is not defined for any asyncio type.
# __or__:  false for all 10 — bitwise OR is not defined for any asyncio type.
# __xor__: false for all 10 — bitwise XOR is not defined for any asyncio type.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. Bitwise set-algebra operators (&, |, ^) are entirely absent
#   from the asyncio type hierarchy.
# asyncio.Event note: although Event represents a boolean condition, it does
#   not support boolean algebra operators — combinations of events are
#   expressed through asyncio.gather() or asyncio.wait(), not & / | / ^.
# asyncio.Queue note: Queue is a data structure, but it does not implement
#   set-algebra — it is a FIFO ordered store, not an unordered set. The
#   PriorityQueue and LifoQueue variants also lack set-algebra operators.
# asyncio.Semaphore note: the permit counter is a positive integer, but
#   bitwise operators are not exposed. Only acquire()/release() interact
#   with the counter value.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

